El Quijote Wordcloud¶

Word Cloud is a visual representation of words of a text corpus, where the word’s visual size is proportional to the frequency or importance of the word in such text. Besides that, there is no limit in the text input or the shape of the wordcloud.

Here we will obtain a wordcloud of the book Don Quijote de la Mancha, using as shape an image of two of its protagonists.

First, we need to import the needed libraries

In [2]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import os
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS

The text is extracted from a .txt file inside our working directory

In [3]:
text = open(('DONQ.txt'),encoding="utf8").read()

The basic tools for creating a wordcloud are set. To use a mask numpy must be imported, to convert a image file into an array of 1's and 0's.

In [4]:
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
d = path.dirname(__file__) if "__file__" in locals() else os.getcwd()
mask = np.array(Image.open("quij.png"))

If there are words needed to filter, it can be done with

In [5]:
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
#such list can be listed uncommenting the line below
#stop words

The only thing left is creating the wordcloud with proper parameters, and display it using matplotlib

In [6]:
wordcloud = WordCloud(
                     background_color="rgba(255, 255, 255, 0)", mode="RGBA",
#                   background_color='white',
#                   stopwords=STOPWORDS,
                     max_words=60000,
                     max_font_size=60, 
#                   stopwords=None   ,
                     repeat=False   ,
                     min_word_length=5   ,
                      mask=mask,
                     width=3840, height=2160,
                     contour_color='steelblue',
                     collocations=False,
                     random_state=40
                                        ).generate(text)
In [7]:
# Display and save the generated image:
plt.figure( figsize=(38,22) )
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.savefig('quijote.png')
